72. Database Normalization
Definition

Normalization organizes data to reduce duplication and improve consistency.

Problem Without Normalization

Example:

Orders Table
Order_ID
Customer_Name
Customer_Address
Product_Name

Duplicate customer data.

Normalized Design
Customer Table

Customer

id
name
address

Order Table
Order

id
customer_id
product_id

Relationship:

Customer

   |

Orders

Normalization Levels

First Normal Form (1NF)

Rules:

Atomic values
No repeating groups

Bad:

Phone:

1111,2222,3333


Good:

Customer Phone Table
customer_id
phone

Second Normal Form (2NF)

Requirements:

Must be in 1NF
No partial dependency

Example:
Composite key:

(order_id, product_id)


Product information should not depend only on:

product_id

Third Normal Form (3NF)

Requirement:

No transitive dependency.

Example:

Bad:
Employee

employee_id
department_id
department_name

Better:

Employee

employee_id
department_id


Department

department_id
department_name

Advantages of Normalization
Reduces duplicate data
Improves consistency
Easier updates
Better integrity
## Disadvantages
More joins
Query complexi
Slower reads

73. Database Denormalization
Definition

Adding duplicate data intentionally to improve read performance.
Example:

Normalized:
Orders

order_id
customer_id


Customer

customer_id
name
Requires JOIN.

Denormalized:

Orders

order_id
customer_id
customer_name
No JOIN required.

Why Denormalize?

When:

Read traffic is high
Joins are expensive
Performance is critical
Examples
Social Media Feed
Store:

Post

post_id
content
user_name
profile_image

instead of joining user table.

Trade-off

| Normalization      | Denormalization  |
| ------------------ | ---------------- |
| Less duplication   | More duplication |
| Better consistency | Faster reads     |
| More joins         | Less joins       |

Normalization improves data integrity, while denormalization improves read performance by reducing joins